We need to show that \mathfrak {F} _j  \vcentcolon \equiv   \{  x  \in  L  \mid  j(x) = x  \} is
(1) closed under arbitrary meets and is (2) an exponential ideal.


    Let S  \subseteq   \mathfrak {F} _j. To show that \left ( \bigwedge  S \right )  \in         \mathfrak {F} _j, we have to show \left ( \bigwedge  S \right ) is itself a fixed
    point of j, for which it suffices to show j \left ( \bigwedge  S \right )        \le   \bigwedge  S. Consider some x  \in  S, which satisfies x = j(x) by
    the definition of S. To show j( \bigwedge  S)  \le  j(x), it suffices
    to show \bigwedge  S  \le  x which holds by definition.



    Let x  \in  L, y  \in   \mathfrak {F} _j. We need to show that
    j(x  \Rightarrow  y)  \in   \mathfrak {F} _j i.e. j(x  \Rightarrow  y)  \le  x  \Rightarrow  y.
    By the definition of Heyting implication, we just have to show
    j(x  \Rightarrow  y)  \wedge  x  \le  y. This is the case since we have

       \usepackage {amsmath}
       \usepackage {amsfonts}
       \usepackage {amssymb}
       \usepackage {mathtools}
    \begin {tabular}{l l l l}
      ~                             & ~     & ~ & ~ \\ 
      $j(x  \Rightarrow  y)  \wedge  x$ & $ \le $ & $j(x  \Rightarrow  y)  \wedge  j(x)$ &  \textsf {[inflationarity]} \\ 
      ~                             & $ \le $ & $j((x  \Rightarrow  y)  \wedge  x)$  &  \textsf {[meet-preservation]}  \\ 
      ~                             & $ \le $ & $j(y)$ &  \textsf {[modus ponens]} \\ 
      ~                             & $ \le $ & $y$    &  \textsf {[$y$ is a fixed point of $j$]}
       \end {tabular}
